<HEAD>U.N. Official Hopes Bush MorehSympathetic to Population Program</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JIM ABRAMS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The head of the U.N. Population agency said Friday
she hoped new U.S. President George Bush would end a three-year U.S.
Boycott of agency funding programs linked to alleged coercive
abortions in China.
   Dr. Nafis Sadik, executive director of the U.N. Fund for
Population Activities, said, ``we see a new opportunity with the new
administration'' for resuming U.S. Participation in family planning
programs.
   The United States has withheld about $85 million from the UNFPA
since 1985, charging that Chinese family planning programs backed by
the UNFPA involve coercive abortions.
   ``We are not supporting any abortion program anywhere in the
world,'' Sadik said. She said Chinese officials had stressed to her
that although there are isolated cases of coercion, China does not
force women to undergo abortions.
   She said Bush was ``strongly supportive of population policies''
when he was U.S. Ambassador to the U.N. in 1971-73 and should have
special sympathy for China, where he also lived in 1974-75 as head
of the U.S. Liaison office.
   Sadik, from Pakistan, said she also told the Chinese that they
should work harder to improve the image of their family planning
program, which is striving to hold down a population which has
reached 1.1 billion.
   Since 1980 China has tried to enforce a one-child per couple
policy. The policy has had some successes in the cities, but has met
resistance in the countryside where the return of family farming has
made it advantageous to have more children.
   Newly affluent farmers are also willing to pay heavy fines
imposed for giving birth to two or more children. After dipping in
the early 1980s, the rate of population growth has begun to creep up
again, and demographers now estimate the population at the end of
the century will be about 1.28 billion, well above the original
target of 1.2 billion.
   The Chinese, Dr. Sadik said, ''are not quite sure what they can
do to increase acceptance of family planning.''
   She said the stress is on more thorough education and better
clinical services.
   The UNFPA, she said, is urging China to improve the quality of
its contraceptive devices.
   Prod A. Laquian, deputy representative of the UNFPA in Beijing,
said 50 million Chinese woven wear a stainless steel intrauterine
device that is often ineffective as a contraceptive.
   He said 10 percent of women wearing the IUD become pregnant, and
that 50 to 70 percent of women who obtain abortions were usng the
faultylIUDs.
   Dr. Sadik said production of effective contraceptives will be the
top priority in a proposed 57-million-U.S. dollar UNFPA aid program
for China in the 1990-94 period. Funding will also go to maternal
and child health, information and publicity for family planning,
demographic training and programs for women.
   She said the program will be presented to the UNFPA Governing
Council in June, at which time the United States, a member of the
council, will have to take a stand. ``My hope is that the United
States and China don't want a confrontation.''
   The UNFPA will have a budget this year of about 190 million
dollars, with China the second largest recipient of funds after
India.
   Dr. Sadik said African countries, many which have just begun
family planning programs, have been the worst hit by the withdrawal
of U.S. funds.
   She said other donors have increased their contributions in
recent years. But she said that as a result of the U.S. pullout
``we've had to stretch the programs out, and reduce their scope. We
did lose some momentum.''
