<HEAD>Senators Will Push for Aid to UN Family Planning Agency</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: SUBS 3rd graf pvs, Supporters of, to CLARIFY supporters not
talking specifically about override; picks up 4th graf, Adding to</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JIM DRINKARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Four senators told President Bush Thursday
that Congress will press again this year for a U.S. contribution to
the United Nations population control agency, a fight that led to a
veto of last year's foreign aid bill.
   The lawmakers said Third World population growth poses ``a grave
threat to our own future security'' because of the increasing
pressures it places on the environment and on the political
stability of poor countries.
   Supporters of aid to the U.N. Population Fund dropped a $15
million appropriation for the agency as part of a compromise after
Bush vetoed the foreign aid bill last year. But they believe they
have a better chance of getting the aid approved because of growing
GOP restiveness on the abortion issue.
   Adding to their optimism is an agreement by the U.N. agency to
allow the United States to earmark its population aid for specific
countries whose family planning practices do not run counter to the
president's abortion stand.
   The House and Senate voted to send money to the agency last
year, which would have reversed a 5-year-old Reagan administration
policy. Anti-abortion forces objected because the agency sends
money to China, which uses coercion and abortion to enforce a
one-child-per-family policy.
   But Sens. Patrick Leahy, D-Vt., Barbara Mikulski, D-Md., Mark
Hatfield, R-Ore., and Nancy Kassebaum, R-Kan., told Bush in the
letter Thursday that the U.N. agency does not support abortion and
has guaranteed it will not use American money in China.
   ``With the population of the developing countries projected to
grow by over 900 million during the 1990s ... we cannot afford to
remain outside the UNFPA,'' the senators wrote.
   A group of moderate House and Senate Republicans sent a similar
letter last month to Secretary of State James A. Baker III calling
for renewal of U.S. funding for the UNFPA.
   Last year's veto ``sent the wrong signal to the American public
and the international community regarding the Republican Party's
support for international family planning services,'' they wrote.
</TEXT>
