<LEADPARA>  A U.N. agency said Wednesday that the planet's problems can be put simply:
People are ruining the place.;   The future as seen by the U.N. Population
Fund's report is not pretty. Cities will sink into squalor, water will be too
dirty to drink, forests will be cut down, land will be destroyed by bad
farming, poverty will continue to increase.  </LEADPARA>
<SECTION>  Front  </SECTION>
<HEADLINE>  WORLD'S FUTURE CALLED GLOOMY
POPULATION GROWTH HURTS ENVIRONMENT, U.N. REPORT
SAYS  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>     "Population growth has a profoundly adverse effect on the environment," the
report issued Wednesday said.;   The same agency reported in May that world
population was expected to reach 5.4 billion by the middle of this year and
could increase to 10.2 billion by the year 2050, 25 years ahead of earlier
estimates.;   That report said the world fertility rate must be reduced from
3.8 births per woman to 3.3, and in line with that, the new report said world
population growth must be balanced against the resources to handle it.;
"Every year of delayed action brings us closer to the brink -- the red line of
resource collapse and social dislocation that humanity must never cross," the
new report said.;   That may have happened already in some of the world's
poorer countries, where population pressures are at their greatest, it said.
And things could turn ugly in the cities.;   "If the 'million-plus' cities
continue to mushroom at current rates, transport, communication, health and
sanitation systems could be overwhelmed and political systems endangered," the
report said.;   "Nonsense," said Housing Secretary Jack Kemp, when asked about
the report, which he called "typical of at least that agency of the U.N.";
"People are not a drain on the resources of the planet," Kemp said.;   The
United States has refused to give money to the U.N. Population Fund since the
1980s because the agency operates in China, which has coercive
population-control policies that have included forced sterilization and forced
abortion.;   A foreign aid bill stalled in the House would provide $20 million
for the agency this year, but President Bush has threatened a veto if the bill
passes with that provision in it.;   Environmental groups, including Zero
Population Growth, the National Audubon Society, the Population Institute, the
National Wildlife Federation and the Population Crisis Committee, lined up
Wednesday to hail the U.N. report.;   "We call upon the Bush administration
and Congress to take aggressive leadership to address the population emergency
today," said Nancy Wallace, Washington director of the Sierra Club's
international population program.;   "We can't begin to talk about the
environment, the economy or human suffering on this planet without addressing
the population crisis," she said.  </TEXT>
