<HEAD>Senators to Push U.S. Aid for Family Planning</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JIM DRINKARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Backers of U.S. support for a United Nations
family-planning agency are seeking to reverse President Bush's
decision to exclude the organization from this year's foreign aid
bill.
   Four senators _ two Democrats and two Republicans _ told Bush in
a letter Thursday that they hope for a compromise. Failing that,
they said they plan to force the issue, which led to a veto of last
year's foreign aid bill.
   Both the House and Senate voted last year to give $15 million to
the United Nations Population Fund, known as UNFPA, to help carry
out its family planning activities in more than 140 countries
around the world.
   But the provision ultimately was dropped from the foreign aid
bill after Bush vetoed the measure. The White House had come under
heavy pressure from anti-abortion forces who complained that the
agency operates programs in China, which uses forced abortions and
sterilizations to carry out its one-child-per-family policy.
   In their letter, Sens. Patrick Leahy, D-Vt.; Barbara Mikulski,
D-Md.; Nancy Kassebaum, R-Kan.; and Mark Hatfield, R-Ore., argued
that Third World population growth poses ``a grave threat to our
own future security'' because of the increasing pressures it places
on the environment and on the political stability of poor countries.
   Supporters of aid to UNFPA are optimistic they can prevail this
time around, in part because the population agency is willing to
provide extraordinary safeguards to make sure the money is not used
in China and in part because of growing GOP fear of highlighting
the abortion issue.
   The senators told Bush that UNFPA has agreed to permit the
United States to earmark its population aid for specific countries
whose family planning practices are in line with U.S. values, and
will allow audits to make sure the money isn't freeing other funds
for use in China.
   The agency has received no U.S. aid since President Reagan
halted it more than five years ago, and a congressional source said
it is anxious to regain American participation ``for the
symbolism'' as much as for the money. UNFPA expects that if the
United States resumes participation, its contributions would grow
in later years, said the source, who demanded anonymity.
   ``With the population of the developing countries projected to
grow by over 900 million during the 1990s ... we cannot afford to
remain outside the UNFPA,'' the senators wrote.
   ``Renewed confrontation serves no one's interest,'' they said,
asking the administration to open discussions with Capitol Hill
aimed at finding a compromise.
   A group of moderate House and Senate Republicans sent a similar
letter last month to Secretary of State James A. Baker III calling
for renewal of U.S. aid to UNFPA and chastising opponents for
miscasting the argument as an abortion issue.
   Bush's veto last year ``sent the wrong signal to the American
public and the international community regarding the Republican
Party's support for international family planning services,'' they
wrote.
   ``This is a women's issue, a family issue, an environmental
issue and an international security issue,'' said the GOP group,
which included two women House members running for the Senate this
year _ Reps. Lynn Martin of Illinois and Claudine Schneider of
Rhode Island. ``It remains an issue of great importance to the
Republican Party.''
