<HEAD>U.N. Official Hopes Bush More Sympathetic to Population Program</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JIM ABRAMS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A U.N. official said Friday she hopes President
Bush will end a three-year boycott of U.N. family-planning programs
that Washington has accused of supporting forced abortions in China.
   Nafis Sadik, executive director of the U.N. Fund for Population
Activities, said, ``We see a new opportunity with the new
administration.''
   The United States has withheld about $85 million from the agency
since 1985, charging that Chinese family-planning programs backed by
the agency involve forced abortions.
   However, Ms. Sadik said Friday, ``We are not supporting any
abortion program anywhere in the world.''
   She also said Chinese officials had stressed to her that although
isolated cases of coercion do crop up, China does not force women to
undergo abortions.
   Ms. Sadik said Bush ws ``strongly supportive of population
policies'' as U.S. ambassador to the United Nations in 1971-73. She
also said he should have ``special sympathy for China,'' where he
lived in 1974-75 as head of the U.S. liaison office.
   Ms. Sadik, of Pakistan, said she also told the Chinese they
should work harder to improve the image of their family-planning
program.
   Chinese officials are striving to hold down a population of 1.1
billion, the largest in the world. Since 1980, they have tried to
enforce a one-child per couple policy.
   The policy has met some success in the cities but encountered
resistance in the countryside, where the return of family farming
has made it advantageous to have more children. Newly affluent
farmers are often willing to pay heavy fines imposed for giving
birth to two or more children.
   After dipping in the early 1980s, the rate of population growth
has begun to creep up again. Demographers estimate the population at
the end of the century will be about 1.28 billion, 80 million above
the original target.
   However, Sadik said African countries, many of which have just
begun family-planning programs, were hit hardest by the withdrawal
of U.S. funds.
