<LEADPARA>  Declaring earlier projections too optimistic, the United Nations Population
Fund said Monday the number of people in the world will more than double -- to
11.6 billion -- before stabilizing sometime in the 22nd century.;    The fund
had projected two years ago that population would stabilize at around 10.2
billion by about 2085.  </LEADPARA>
<SECTION>  Front  </SECTION>
<HEADLINE>  POPULATION GROWING FASTER THAN THOUGHT
U.N. AGENCY SEES 10 BILLION IN WORLD BY THE
YEAR 2050  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>     The current "most likely" projection calls for a population of 10 billion
in 2050 with continued growth for an additional 100 years, leveling off at
11.6 billion, the organization said in a "State of World Population" report.;
  The largest growth will be in some of the world's most densely populated
areas. South Asia, where millions are threatened by sickness, hunger and
exposure following an April 30 cyclone in Bangladesh, will grow by 300 million
between now and the end of this century, the U.N. organization said.;    And
the population of Africa, which currently is in the grips of an AIDS pandemic,
will be growing faster in 2000 than today's world average -- even if the
worst-case death rate from AIDS develops.;    The world's population is
expected to pass 5.4 billion sometime this year.;    Higher levels;  "By 2001,
the total will be 6.4 billion," the fund reported. "As for eventual totals,
recent work by the U.N. population division suggests that population growth
will stop much later and at much higher levels than previously thought.;
"Instead of a stable total of about 10.2 billion in 2085 . . . population may
eventually level off at about 11.6 billion.";    The "most likely" growth
projection assumes that the amount currently being spent on contraceptives and
family planning services will double to $9 billion a year by 2000 and that the
number of couples in developing countries who use contraceptives will increase
from 381 million to 567 million.;    "Without dramatic increases in funds for
family planning, there is no possibility of stabilizing world population at
moderate levels," said Dr. Nafis Sadik, a Pakistani physician who heads the
Population Fund.;    "Right now, we are simply running to stay in place," she
added.;    If family planning were universally available and widespread use
achieved within this decade, the planet's population would stabilize at about
9 billion sometime in the next century, the fund said.;    Under a projection
that assumes slower growth in family planning and contraception, the
population would exceed 14 billion before finally stabilizing, the fund said.;
   Affordable prevention;  "The fact that the projections are being revised
upward is the bad news," said Sharon Camp, vice president of the
Washington-based Population Crisis Committee. "The good news is we know what
we have to do and it's entirely affordable.";    The $9 billion annual price
tag for achieving population stability at 11.6 billion includes assistance
provided by governments of developing countries, aid from the developed world
and money spent by individual users of family planning services.;    Camp said
the Bush administration "shows no sign of being at all seized with the world
population problem or having any concern about family planning.";    She said
a 335-page White House proposal for a new foreign aid authorization bill
contained only 55 lines on family "and 38 of those lines were devoted to
restrictions" on how funds could be spent.  </TEXT>
